## Context Discipline

Keep the root/main conversation thread as **pure orchestration**. Route read-heavy, exploratory, or fan-out work into sub-tasks/subagents so that raw tool output (file bodies, grep results, log dumps, web pages) never lands in the main context.

**Core rules:**

- Delegate by default when a conclusion requires sweeping many files or URLs. Search directly only for a single, known-location fact.
- Delegates must **return distilled conclusions** — `file:line` + findings — not raw dumps. If the downstream agent pastes file bodies back, the context savings are lost.
- For long multi-phase tasks: persist a short progress/design note (use the memory system or a scratch file) and **reset context between phases** (`ESC ESC` to return to an earlier checkpoint) rather than carrying intermediate work forward.
{{- if hasSuffix "/CLAUDE.md" $.chezmoi.targetFile }}

**Claude Code specifics:**

- Use the **`@scout`** subagent for read-only codebase location tasks (find where X is defined, which files reference Y). It runs on Sonnet, enforces a conclusions-only return contract, and keeps exploration out of the main window. The built-in `Explore` subagent is equivalent but uncontracted — prefer `@scout` when the root-thread guard would block a direct `Read`/`Grep`.
- Use the **`@distill`** subagent to summarize large files, diffs, or command output — paste only the summary back, not the source.
- Use the **Workflow tool** (available in Opus 4.8+ sessions) for deterministic fan-out when work decomposes into independent parallel steps. The Workflow tool keeps the main thread as a pure orchestrator and isolates each worker in its own context.
- The statusline `ctx:NN%` turns **yellow at 20%** and **red at 25%** — treat either color as a cue to delegate the next read or reset to a pre-read checkpoint. The guard fires early by design: past 20% you've likely already let content into context that should have gone to a subagent.
- **Root-thread guard**: a `PreToolUse` hook uses an **allowlist model** — only orchestration tools (`Agent`/`Task`, `Write`/`Edit`, task-tracking, `Workflow`, `Skill`, etc.) are permitted in the root thread. Everything else is blocked by default: `Read`, `Grep`, `Glob`, `Bash`, `WebFetch`, `WebSearch`, all `mcp__*` tools, `ReadMcpResourceTool`, `TaskOutput`, and any future tool not explicitly on the list. This is intentional: the root thread is for decisions, not execution, and new tools are safe-by-default. Exception: `Read` of self-authored scratch files (`~/.claude/plans/` and `~/.claude/projects/*/memory/`) is allowed in root so that editing plan and memory files doesn't require the sentinel. To disable the guard entirely: **ask the user first**, then create `~/.claude/root-guard-exempt` via the Write tool. Never create the sentinel without explicit user approval — it bypasses a deliberate constraint.
{{- else if hasSuffix "/.pi/agent/AGENTS.md" $.chezmoi.targetFile }}

**pi specifics:**

- Use the `subagent` tool for any read-heavy, exploratory, shell, or MCP task. Choose `scout` for reconnaissance, `planner` for plans, `reviewer` for review, and `worker` for implementation. All managed roles have `mcp`; scout, planner, and reviewer use it for read-only external-service lookups, including Riot-machine-only Jira, Notion, and P4 lookups. Require a concise `file:line` findings handoff.
- `PI_ROOT_PHASE` propagates the root session phase to every child, including nested children. Only `PI_ROOT_PHASE=execute` retains an agent's declared execution class; plan, missing, legacy `normal`, or unrecognized phase values downgrade it to `read-only`, where reads, scratchpad, and read-only MCP calls remain available while mutations are blocked. Outside plan mode, Git workers still require an approved worktree; a markerless `worktree-write` worker in a confirmed non-Git/P4 cwd may mutate locally and call mutating MCP tools. Git-cwd and ambiguous probe cases fail closed. Mutating MCP calls are separately classified by the `mcp-mutation-policy` denylist.
- The root-thread guard is a hard block in `tui` and `rpc` sessions: only orchestration tools, task/worktree tools, and `read` under plans, the global skill roots (`~/.pi/agent/skills`, `~/.agents/skills`), or repo `todo.txt`/`done.txt` are permitted. `read`, `grep`, `find`, `ls`, `bash`, `mcp`, and unknown tools must be delegated.
- JSON subagents and print-mode one-shots keep their own plan-mode extension inert, but inherit `PI_ROOT_PHASE` so the launcher enforces the root's plan-phase read-only policy. There is no root-guard escape hatch; change the managed extension only when deliberately changing policy.
- Subagent child launches must retain normal context-file discovery; never pass `--no-context-files` or `-nc`. `--no-session` isolates session history only and remains intentional.
- `/plan` is interactive-root-only. Spawned JSON workers do not enable their own plan-mode extension, but inherit `PI_ROOT_PHASE` and are downgraded to read-only while the root remains in plan phase.
- The root alone owns `worktree_start`, `worktree_status`, and `worktree_stop`. Before delegating implementation, activate one worktree; workers receive a topology-validated initial cwd automatically, use direct Git there, and must not invoke worktree lifecycle tools. This is cooperative launch routing, not path containment: workers must not access paths outside their assigned worktree.
{{- end }}

## Mode discipline

- When planning (scoping a non-trivial task / "plan mode"): invoke the `my-planning` skill before producing the plan.
- When implementing (accept-edits / execution): invoke the `my-execution` skill.
- When reviewing a diff, PR, or commit — including self-review of your own work: invoke the `my-code-review` skill.
- Before presenting any plan for approval, run the `my-code-review` self-review pass (a fresh sub-agent) and address its findings first.

## Always-on guardrails — read the referenced skill before acting in its domain; don't rely on remembering it

- Follow `my-git` for every git action: push immediately after every commit, and make file edits only inside an isolated git worktree (hook-enforced).
- Follow `my-task-tracking`: maintain an active tasklist every session.
- Follow `my-agent-memory`: treat learning-as-instructions as continuous, and capture durable learnings as skills.
- Follow `my-engineering-principles`: less is more, and it applies to code.
- Follow `my-writing` for design/technical prose (README intros, design docs, project retrospectives): read it before drafting, and defer PR/commit/incident text to `my-audit-trail`.
- Follow `my-commenting` for every comment or docstring: explain durable WHY, not what; never leak task/PR/ticket narrative into the source.

[less-is-more]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Less_is_more
